hands_on_practices.solution:
The object to compute is the contact term part of the expression $\partial_x^\mu \partial_y^ho \langle \mathcal{T} B_{\mu
u}(x) B_{ho\sigma}(y) angle$.
We start with the given momentum space representation of the two-point function:
$$
\langle \mathcal{T} B_{\mu
u}(x) B_{ho\sigma}(y) angle = \int  rac{d^D p}{(2\pi)^D} e^{-ip(x-y)} i\Delta_{\mu
u,ho\sigma}(p)
$$
We need to apply the derivatives $\partial_x^\mu$ and $\partial_y^ho$. The derivatives act on the exponential factor $e^{-ip(x-y)}$.
$$
\partial_x^\mu e^{-ip(x-y)} = -ip^\mu e^{-ip(x-y)}
$$
$$
\partial_y^ho e^{-ip(x-y)} = ip^ho e^{-ip(x-y)}
$$
Applying both derivatives to the two-point function gives:
$$
\partial_x^\mu \partial_y^ho \langle \mathcal{T} B_{\mu
u}(x) B_{ho\sigma}(y) angle = \int  rac{d^D p}{(2\pi)^D} (-ip^\mu)(ip^ho) e^{-ip(x-y)} i\Delta_{\mu
u,ho\sigma}(p) = \int  rac{d^D p}{(2\pi)^D} e^{-ip(x-y)} \left( p^\mu p^ho i\Delta_{\mu
u,ho\sigma}(p) ight)
$$
Let's denote the momentum-space expression as $\mathcal{C}_{
u\sigma}(p) = p^\mu p^ho i\Delta_{\mu
u,ho\sigma}(p)$.
We use the given expression for the propagator $i\Delta_{\mu
u,ho\sigma}(p)$:
$$
\mathcal{C}_{
u\sigma}(p) = p^\mu p^ho  rac{i}{p^2} \left[  rac{1}{2}(\eta_{\muho}\eta_{
u\sigma} - \eta_{\mu\sigma}\eta_{
uho}) -  rac{1-\xi}{p^2} (p_\mu p_ho \eta_{
u\sigma} - p_\mu p_\sigma \eta_{
uho} - p_
u p_ho \eta_{\mu\sigma} + p_
u p_\sigma \eta_{\muho}) ight]
$$
Let's compute the contraction term by term.

First term:
$$
p^\mu p^ho \left[  rac{1}{2}(\eta_{\muho}\eta_{
u\sigma} - \eta_{\mu\sigma}\eta_{
uho}) ight] =  rac{1}{2} (p_\mu p^\mu \eta_{
u\sigma} - p_\sigma p_
u) =  rac{1}{2} (p^2 \eta_{
u\sigma} - p_
u p_\sigma)
$$

Second term, we contract $p^\mu p^ho$ with $K_{\mu
u,ho\sigma}^{(p)} = (p_\mu p_ho \eta_{
u\sigma} - p_\mu p_\sigma \eta_{
uho} - p_
u p_ho \eta_{\mu\sigma} + p_
u p_\sigma \eta_{\muho})$:
 egin{align*}
p^\mu p^ho K_{\mu
u,ho\sigma}^{(p)} &= p^\mu p^ho (p_\mu p_ho \eta_{
u\sigma}) - p^\mu p^ho (p_\mu p_\sigma \eta_{
uho}) - p^\mu p^ho (p_
u p_ho \eta_{\mu\sigma}) + p^\mu p^ho (p_
u p_\sigma \eta_{\muho}) \
&= (p^\mu p_\mu)(p^ho p_ho) \eta_{
u\sigma} - (p^\mu p_\mu) (p^ho p_\sigma) \eta_{
uho} - p_
u (p^ho p_ho) (p^\mu \eta_{\mu\sigma}) + p_
u p_\sigma (p^\mu p^ho \eta_{\muho}) \
&= (p^2)(p^2) \eta_{
u\sigma} - p^2 (p_\sigma p^ho \eta_{
uho}) - p_
u p^2 (p^\mu \eta_{\mu\sigma}) + p_
u p_\sigma (p^\mu p_\mu) \
&= p^4 \eta_{
u\sigma} - p^2 p_\sigma p_
u - p^2 p_
u p_\sigma + p^2 p_
u p_\sigma \
&= p^4 \eta_{
u\sigma} - p^2 p_
u p_\sigma
\end{align*}

Now, we assemble the full expression for $\mathcal{C}_{
u\sigma}(p)$:
 egin{align*}
\mathcal{C}_{
u\sigma}(p) &=  rac{i}{p^2} \left[  rac{1}{2}(p^2 \eta_{
u\sigma} - p_
u p_\sigma) ight] -  rac{i(1-\xi)}{p^4} \left[ p^4 \eta_{
u\sigma} - p^2 p_
u p_\sigma ight] \
&= i \left[  rac{1}{2}(\eta_{
u\sigma} -  rac{p_
u p_\sigma}{p^2}) ight] - i(1-\xi) \left[ \eta_{
u\sigma} -  rac{p_
u p_\sigma}{p^2} ight] \
&= i \left(  rac{1}{2} - (1-\xi) ight) \left( \eta_{
u\sigma} -  rac{p_
u p_\sigma}{p^2} ight) \
&= i \left( \xi -  rac{1}{2} ight) \left( \eta_{
u\sigma} -  rac{p_
u p_\sigma}{p^2} ight)
\end{align*}
So, we have:
$$
\partial_x^\mu \partial_y^ho \langle \mathcal{T} B_{\mu
u}(x) B_{ho\sigma}(y) angle = \int  rac{d^D p}{(2\pi)^D} e^{-ip(x-y)} i \left( \xi -  rac{1}{2} ight) \left( \eta_{
u\sigma} -  rac{p_
u p_\sigma}{p^2} ight)
$$
Contact terms in position space correspond to terms that are polynomials in momentum in momentum space. We must identify the polynomial part of $\mathcal{C}_{
u\sigma}(p)$.
$$
\mathcal{C}_{
u\sigma}(p) = i \left( \xi -  rac{1}{2} ight) \eta_{
u\sigma} - i \left( \xi -  rac{1}{2} ight)  rac{p_
u p_\sigma}{p^2}
$$
The first term, $i ( \xi - 1/2 ) \eta_{
u\sigma}$, is a constant with respect to momentum, so it is a polynomial of degree zero. Its Fourier transform will yield a contact term.
The second term, $- i ( \xi - 1/2 ) p_
u p_\sigma/p^2$, is not a polynomial in momentum. Its Fourier transform is non-local and corresponds to long-range contributions, not contact terms. For example, in $D=4$, $\int d^4p \, e^{-ipx}/p^2 \propto 1/x^2$.

The contact term part of the double divergence is the Fourier transform of the polynomial part of $\mathcal{C}_{
u\sigma}(p)$:
$$
	ext{Contact Terms} = \int  rac{d^D p}{(2\pi)^D} e^{-ip(x-y)} \left[ i \left( \xi -  rac{1}{2} ight) \eta_{
u\sigma} ight]
$$
Using the integral representation of the Dirac delta function, $\int  rac{d^D p}{(2\pi)^D} e^{-ip(x-y)} = \delta^D(x-y)$, we get:
$$
	ext{Contact Terms} = i \left( \xi -  rac{1}{2} ight) \eta_{
u\sigma} \delta^D(x-y)
$$
This is the final expression for the contact terms.
